# 🧠 What is a JOIN?

A **JOIN** combines rows from two or more tables based on a related column.

Example relationship:

```
CUSTOMER_DETALES.CUSTOMER_ID = ORDERS.CUSTOMER_ID
```

---

# 🔥 1️⃣ INNER JOIN

👉 Returns only matching records from both tables.

### Example: Get Customer Name with Orders

```sql
SELECT C.CUSTOMER_NAME,
       O.ORDER_ID,
       O.STATUS,
       O.TOTAL_AMOUNT
FROM CUSTOMER_DETALES C
INNER JOIN ORDERS O
ON C.CUSTOMER_ID = O.CUSTOMER_ID;
```

✅ Shows only customers who placed orders.

---

# 🔥 2️⃣ LEFT JOIN (LEFT OUTER JOIN)

👉 Returns all records from left table + matching from right.

```sql
SELECT C.CUSTOMER_NAME,
       O.ORDER_ID
FROM CUSTOMER_DETALES C
LEFT JOIN ORDERS O
ON C.CUSTOMER_ID = O.CUSTOMER_ID;
```

✅ Shows all customers
❌ If no order → ORDER_ID = NULL

---

# 🔥 3️⃣ RIGHT JOIN

👉 Returns all records from right table + matching from left.

```sql
SELECT C.CUSTOMER_NAME,
       O.ORDER_ID
FROM CUSTOMER_DETALES C
RIGHT JOIN ORDERS O
ON C.CUSTOMER_ID = O.CUSTOMER_ID;
```

---

# 🔥 4️⃣ FULL OUTER JOIN

👉 Returns all records from both tables.

```sql
SELECT C.CUSTOMER_NAME,
       O.ORDER_ID
FROM CUSTOMER_DETALES C
FULL OUTER JOIN ORDERS O
ON C.CUSTOMER_ID = O.CUSTOMER_ID;
```

---

# 🔥 5️⃣ JOIN with Multiple Tables

Example: Get Supplier Name with Food Items

```sql
SELECT F.FOOD_NAME,
       S.SUPPLIER_NAME,
       F.PRICE
FROM FOOD_ITEMS F
JOIN SUPPLIERS S
ON F.SUPPLIER_ID = S.SUPPLIER_ID;
```

---

# 🔥 6️⃣ Join 3 Tables (Real Interview Query)

Customer → Orders → Distribution Center

```sql
SELECT C.CUSTOMER_NAME,
       O.ORDER_ID,
       D.CENTER_NAME,
       O.TOTAL_AMOUNT
FROM ORDERS O
JOIN CUSTOMER_DETALES C
ON O.CUSTOMER_ID = C.CUSTOMER_ID
JOIN DISTRIBUTION_CENTERS D
ON O.CENTER_ID = D.CENTER_ID;
```

🔥 This is real production-level query.

---

# 🔥 7️⃣ SELF JOIN

Example: Suppose suppliers are in same city

```sql
SELECT A.SUPPLIER_NAME AS SUPPLIER1,
       B.SUPPLIER_NAME AS SUPPLIER2,
       A.CITY
FROM SUPPLIERS A
JOIN SUPPLIERS B
ON A.CITY = B.CITY
AND A.SUPPLIER_ID <> B.SUPPLIER_ID;
```

---

# 🎯 Visual Understanding

| Join Type  | Returns                   |
| ---------- | ------------------------- |
| INNER JOIN | Only matching rows        |
| LEFT JOIN  | All left + matching right |
| RIGHT JOIN | All right + matching left |
| FULL JOIN  | All from both tables      |

---

# 🚀 Interview-Level Question

### Find top 5 customers by total spending:

```sql
SELECT C.CUSTOMER_NAME,
       SUM(O.TOTAL_AMOUNT) AS TOTAL_SPENT
FROM ORDERS O
JOIN CUSTOMER_DETALES C
ON O.CUSTOMER_ID = C.CUSTOMER_ID
GROUP BY C.CUSTOMER_NAME
ORDER BY TOTAL_SPENT DESC
LIMIT 5;
```

---

# ⚡ Important Join Tips (Snowflake)

* Always use table aliases (C, O, D)
* Use fully qualified names in production
* Check duplicate rows when joining many-to-many

